What happens to my e-mail on the way?
E-mail is actually electronic mail.
Was the Internet e-mail service designed with a similar technical approach to traditional mail?
The design of the early Internet services was focused on making communication possible.
The basic technical protocols therefore failed to provide a solid basis for an audible exchange of letters.
So a conventional e-mail is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
When user "Anna" emails "Benni", are the two computers directly connected?
Anna's e-mail program or browser first sends the mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if she has a Gmail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run through several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can call his provider and see what's in it.
Are traditional e-mails being read on their way through the web?
Most e-mails are read multiple times by software robots on the move.
The sender's provider usually checks that the e-mail contains a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also performed on the receiving systems.
The providers also check whether it is a nuisance and unwanted spam that is deleted immediately or at least sorted into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another job?
In systems like Gmail, the robot also collects the information that Google needs to place contextual ads.
When Anna and Benni communicate about their upcoming vacation via Gmail, Google can display relevant links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people read the e-mails?
The likelihood of unauthorized persons reading an email is extremely low.
But in theory, it is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the ability to read e-mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal options to intercept or take note of e-mails.
And then there's the potential for illegal espionage.
Is it possible to protect e-mails from being read?
An openPGP standard encryption can effectively encrypt an e-mail against reading.
It is also possible, with considerable technical effort, to obscure the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even possible to easily identify who has been communicating with whom.
