George Kerevan: European unity gives the Scots a choice
A new day, a new horror story for independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
That provides the key to stories of passport controls at Berwick and a barbed-wire border along Hadrian's Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde proposal pointed to the potential economic benefits of greater freedom of travel in the rest of Europe, but this did not make the headlines as expected.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU Member States often bend their strict rules when it is more favourable for them.
As Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued disregard for Brussels would be only a small concession in return for what is really wanted from the Scots.
So, not really a story.
And one that has come so far in the years that it's already like a fossil: I first heard the phrase "independence means passport control" duck at least 40 years ago.
But an interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance to the European tune?
Why trade the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
The real European news is this: the great postwar plan to unite Europe has come to a standstill.
The euro crisis has officially put an end to the European project.
Throughout the EU, parties that are anti-EU or want to throw the euro as the common currency overboard are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party  founded just this year  won almost five million votes in the September Bundestag elections, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the British equivalent of the Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
The current economic crisis is proving to be a turning point.
The strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket into which the national economies are forced by the adherence to the single currency, have led many to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments creating excessive budget deficits  this was the case only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pegged its members to exchange rates that are advantageous to German exporters  and German politicians would like to leave that to chance.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe will find itself at a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending, spurred on by Berlin.
The current budgetary and monetary problems are caused by a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the green energy directives a code of subsidies for French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers  issued by Brussels, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage fixing in the world does not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and to raise Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policies on Europe, with which the stricken French economy is struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a decisive by-election, pushing the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote  a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split on the right would automatically mean advantages for the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among the white French working class?
It wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections , and this is very possible , then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will converge to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but rather become something like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where does Scotland stand on all this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) Little England.
We can also defend our own economic interests, which includes telling Berlin and Brussels what to do and where to do it.
I suspect Scotland could do quite well in a looser European union if we kept our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise we should consider doing the same as Norway and retaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is  remarkably  the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and implemented) cuts, which were attributed to Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to decide now to become independent, only to be forced to pursue austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty - Growing Up Faster
Research shows that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
Physical changes do not immediately mark puberty
There's no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe the epidemic of obesity is a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter is growing breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are relatively normal among American girls and are the new norm.
I spend a lot of time reassuring parents  usually this is not a sign that puberty is fast approaching, explained Kaplowitz.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, are seen earlier in girls.
However, there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (the onset of the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
Once breast development begins, menopause takes at least two to three years to occur, said Kaplowitz, who also authored the book Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing With This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
There is controversy about what actually marks the beginning of puberty, but "early puberty" is when breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates - something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
If progress is faster, tests by an endocrinologist may be appropriate to rule out serious problems, such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay early menstruation and to prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can ultimately lead to stunted growth and thus low body growth in adults.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication, but he admits:  Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls' feelings of being different from their peers.
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have their period.
They worry about the risk of pregnancy or about how they handle the hygiene side, said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock", recalls a woman whose daughter got her period at ten.
Even though there were early signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home from school scared and excited because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of premature puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz believes the most compelling premise is the obesity epidemic.
He supported the 2001 study of girls aged six to nine years, which linked body fat to puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In that country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend toward full-blown early puberty is not as pronounced as it is in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the subject.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in infants and young children.
"We need to be careful about identifying the true onset of puberty", said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to consult their pediatrician about how to speak to their child.
This may mean having to start a conversation sooner than expected, advised Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it happens sooner than expected.
