New nicotine vaccine could wipe out the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could ruin the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from lifelong nicotine addiction.
More trials are needed, which may take several years, before they can be tested in humans, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results were good.
We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can one day help millions of smokers who have tried to quit, and have tried all the methods available on the market, but have found that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches, says Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information to make nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies chase the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, so a smoker does not experience a nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal activity levels.
In contrast, mice without vaccines would have taken a "break", the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is absolutely safe, could be given to children before they are tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
But more likely, smokers would use it to quit.
They know that when they start smoking again, the nicotine vaccine makes them not feel pleasure, and this helps them to quit the habit, he explains.
