Then, around the turn of the century, I took the next step and I became a vegan.
"The reason for the conviction was not just the diet, but the choice of shoes", says Proctor, who prefers leather to leather.
He realized that other aspects of life could be done without animal products.
First and foremost, being vegan is an ethic.
"I don't want animals to have to die for me", Proctor says, the vegan maxim, which extends to all consumer behavior.
Instead of chasing burgers, scrambled eggs or gummy bears, the vegan quickly discovered completely new products, and enthusiasm grew.
"It's a double bonus", says Proctor today, "being vegan is not really a renunciation, it's not an asceticism, it's an enrichment".
And it is precisely these conditions that have made even the most well-intentioned attempts fail.
"The addiction factor is a major factor in many people's quick quit, much like smoking", says Proctor.
And he adds, "Certain tastes are not to be attached to the animal".
Often the spices or the way the food is prepared are what make it taste good.
"But there are other ways to achieve the same effect", explains the vegan.
For example, at a barbecue Proctor brings eggplants, mushrooms, and some vegan sausages.
He eats a balanced, varied diet that is sure to be hearty.
Of course, you want something between your teeth, that's legitimate.
"It's supposed to taste good, but that's not just reduced to animal feed", said Proctor.
He was not suffering from any health problems, including eating disorders, another widely held belief.
For me, the change had a positive aspect.
I don't take in any foreign cholesterol and I have a high vitamin level.
There are high-performance athletes who eat exclusively vegan.
"My blood counts are fine, I get checked often", says Proctor.
Many critics of vegansimus warn against a lack of vitamin B12.
"Since animals are fed feed rather than grazing on grass, it is questionable whether the meat you buy in the refrigerator is high in vitamin B12", says Proctor.
For vegans, there is also the possibility of taking the coenzyme in tablet form.
"My B12 levels are fine", he explains.
Proctor doesn't have to go far to get food.
After all, basic foods are everywhere, and every supermarket now has soy milk and other products.
I'll find everything I need on the spot.
I only buy something special once in a while.
"Many people overlook the fact that only finished products are expensive, but this is also the case with 'ordinary' finished products".
In any case, vegan dishes are far cheaper and less time-consuming to prepare than is generally believed.
"There is a lot to discover in the home kitchen, and a few little tricks can get you good, if not partially better results", says Proctor.
Margarine instead of butter, a little more baking soda and carbonic acid instead of egg, Proctor was able to amaze his in-laws with his vegan cheesecake.
Family gatherings add a new flavor to the vegan.
It's got a dynamic, when you cook together, it's got a new meaning.
"The situations that can arise are as varied as the people themselves", says Proctor.
But of course, he was met with skepticism.
Don't you like my food?
"Should I feel bad about drinking milk?" - these are the kinds of questions that you have to be very careful about as a vegan.
"I don't reject people, I'm part of this society", Proctor doesn't want to live in an enclave.
And when you look closely, the everyday world doesn't seem as vegan-alien as you might think - and the vegan isn't as restricted in everyday life as you might think.
Fast food is allowed.
There's fries everywhere!
"Many donut shops offer falafel or a vegetarian yufka", says Proctor.
In a pizzeria, he evades the pasta dishes, or he orders a pizza without cheese, all a matter of habit.
The restaurants are so slow to adjust.
"When I started eating vegan 13 years ago, it was much more difficult", the New Zealander can identify a development: "You have to talk to people, make them aware".
"If enough demand comes in, they may be inclined to add to the menu", he hopes.
Vegan restaurants are developing, such as the Mannheim barbecue or the Vogelfrei café.
Proctor wants other restaurants to have at least one vegan dish on the menu.
Basically, there's vegan food for everyone.
Anyone can eat them, so they're the exact opposite of exclusive.
"Meat dishes, on the other hand, are exclusive, in the truest sense of the word, because they exclude others", notes Proctor.
"If you want to avoid food scandals, veganism is a sure way to make most of it impossible in the first place", says Proctor.
But buying vegan products can be a little difficult at first.
Especially when you realize that even peanuts can contain animal additives as colorants, you seem to quickly lose heart in the face of so many obstacles and pitfalls to following ethics.
Not only that, but Reuben Proctor and Lars Thomsen have written a book, Veganissimo - Animal Ingredients and Their Alternatives, which explains the many ingredients used in food and cleaning products.
"Sometimes it's better to take small steps than to stand still or stumble", says Proctor.
Veganism, it's an important moral finger pointing to consciousness.
It may not be able to make you stop, but at least it can teach consumers to question their habits critically.
