Scientists have shed more light on the relationship between a dog's tail wagging and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wagged their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wagged their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say that other dogs can sense and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: "It is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the human brain respond differently to stimuli that trigger positive or negative emotions".
Here we tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just as in humans, the right half of the brain was responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotion.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the lateral tail wagging of their own kind, the researchers monitored the animals as they watched these films of other dogs.
They measured the four-legged man's heart rate and analyzed his behavior.
We'll probably soon understand why the tail moves in one direction and in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs movies with dogs, either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate other distractions, and we were able to control the tail movement more to the left or right".
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog wagging its tail to the right (from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail was leaning mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog wagging), their heart rate would increase and they would look restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not deliberately communicate with one another by these movements.
He is convinced that the dogs learned from experience what movements to worry about and when not to.
He said, "If you have multiple encounters with other dogs and wagging your tail in one direction is more likely to be associated with friendly behavior and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you respond based on those experiences".
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their pets' emotions.
John Bradshaw, a dog behavior expert and visiting fellow at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Medicine, said that this was not the first study to examine whether left and right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when they look at a satisfied dog.
Another study at the University of Victoria in Canada found that dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog if its tail wags to the left rather than the right, rather than becoming restless.
He said the differences could be because the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain hemispheres are used for different purposes, many of the details remain to be determined and dogs are no exception, says Bradshaw.
But since their behavior is easy to record, it probably won't take long to understand why the tail moves sometimes in one direction, sometimes in the other.
