A cry of despair from an Obama voter
I voted for President Obama twice in the hope that change was possible.
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by Republican blockade tactics.
The blockade policy doesn't excuse the Obamacare website problems, the drone attacks
Obama's memoir of the 2008 election campaign is a sad reminder of what could have been
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading a terribly sad book right now.
It's a book I thought would cheer me up and give me hope again during my bleak second year of medical school.
It's called "The Audacity to Win", and it's a memoir of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patient records at night and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and a speech could take your breath away.
The election was a landslide victory and news reporters paused to recall the historic significance of that hour.
My classmates wept for joy, and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House, and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had an approval rating of 82 percent.
And then I close the book.
To switch back to the present is a vicious awakening, like being snatched from a dream.
It's hard to remember those optimistic times, because they seem like a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just not what I imagined.
I recognize the great and diverse things that Obama has accomplished, from passing the Affordable Care Act to health insurance to withdrawing troops from Iraq, ending the forced concealment of homosexuality in the military, and killing Osama bin Laden.
I also believe that the partisan blockade tactic has derailed too many of the efforts that should have moved our nation forward: immigration reform, a public health insurance option, and closing Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times to colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to the end of my explanatory efforts.
I've reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it allows the wiretapping of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on Americans' private lives or why whistleblowers who expose government misconduct are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, or why public funding and spending limits are bypassed during presidential elections.
It does not justify the findings of a report that says the White House's efforts to silence the media are the most "aggressive... since the Nixon administration".
And most recently, it can't excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if this is what I should have expected.
I wonder if I should have known at 18 that government work could conflict with the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the MP position is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events like the Newtown massacre shape public debate.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to be largely chosen by the government itself.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unresolved alternative, he seemed unable to define his direction and positions.
I felt that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard about for so long.
But with Obama's approval ratings dropping below 45 percent this week, it's made it even harder to return to 2008 with this book.
It makes me long for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama had to take a heavy loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with campaign workers after the decision, he told his staff they needed to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to find our magic", he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree with you more.
The views expressed in this commentary are those of Nathaniel Morris alone.
