He took the oath before the 18 black-robed judges of the court, which sits on the Nile and is modeled after an ancient Egyptian temple.
We are striving for a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic, Morsi said at the ceremony, which was broadcast live on state television.
"Today the Egyptian people have laid the foundation for a new life, absolute freedom, real democracy and stability", said Morsi, 60, a US-educated engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been heavily targeted by the government since its inception 84 years ago as a banned organization.
Hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building when Morsi arrived in a small convoy of cars shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
