Traveling through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical aid to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country, there are not many doctors, only one for every 5,000 people
Vote here or on your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to vote for him to be CNN Hero of the Year.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his ailing father lose consciousness and travel to hospitals that lacked the resources to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but then inflammation spread to his brain, causing a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon, says Georges Bwelle.
We would have gotten him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
It is not easy, comments Bwelle.
You can leave your house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has changed little since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, in the United States the ratio is one doctor for every 413 people.
But even if a doctor were available, most Cameroonians would not be able to afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and almost three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
The only problem they have is poverty, says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer made Bwelle decide to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a nonprofit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and provides free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others force themselves into minibuses and ride over unpaved terrain with the medical equipment strapped to the roof to the villages in need.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be greeted like heroes with feasting, singing and dancing and the best accommodations the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a cause for celebration and Bwelle  with his broad smile and boundless energy  is happy to join the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins examining hundreds of patients.
We treat 500 people per trip, says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village  and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates - a document needed for school but simply not affordable for many poor families.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries are usually performed in a school, town hall, or apartment, and after the procedure, patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next patient.
The group's generator powers the lighting for the operating room and the disinfecting equipment, and Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a tiring job, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work, says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team drives back to town, tired but proud of the work they've done.
The group  a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students  performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free surgery he received for a herniated disc enabled him to return to work.
"This changes the future of my family", the man said.
In addition to his weekend clinics and his work as a hospital surgeon, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
This second job finances 60% of his charity work, Bwelle says, with the rest coming from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping", says Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteers with the Bwelles group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go to these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe to support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain practical experience they would never have at home.
We can be on hand for surgeries, helping to draw blood or holding instruments for Dr Bwelle, explains O'Malley.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their own trips to Cameroon and often bring donated medical supplies.
But once in Yaoundé, Bwelle provides accommodation, transportation, and guidance.
"He is a hero without a doubt", says O'Malley.
He has dedicated his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is no burden.
He finds great joy in helping others to live a happier life, thus fulfilling a promise he made to his Father.
I'm so happy when I do this job, says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
