Rainer Schulze is an expert on the Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for his tours is the Cologne Tourism Service Centre directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts off in a very unspectacular way: "We start in the underground garage", says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a city that was car-friendly, and so only what was not too big remained of the remains of the old city wall.
Most users of the parking lot today therefore also rush past the Roman remains and just park their car.
But a closer look reveals an archaeological site on Deck D2, separated by metal bars.
You can see about 15 feet [5 m] high ruins of hand-sized stones.
"They are the remains of the Roman city wall built in the second half of the first century AD", Schulze says.
Before returning to the light of day, Schulze takes the participants to the top level of the parking lot to take a look at a dark, 50-foot-deep shaft.
