John Kerry says in an unprecedented admission that US espionage has "gone inappropriately far".
John Kerry made an unexpected admission, suggesting a softening of the US defensive stance on its surveillance programmes, saying that in some cases the spying had "gone inappropriately far".
The Secretary of State also admitted that he shared responsibility with Barack Obama for switching to "Autopilot" when whistleblower Edward Snowden's explosive revelations about NSA spying became public.
The leaked information has plunged the U.S. government into a diplomatic storm of outrage from its allies.
In a video-conference speech at the Open Government Conference in London, Kerry said: "There is no question that the president and I and others in the government have learned some things that have been on virtual autopilot simply because of the ability to do so, which goes back to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War and of course to 9/11.
He was then the first senior member of the US government to admit that US espionage had crossed a line, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said: 'In some cases, this has gone too far inappropriately.'
The President is determined to provide clarity and is therefore conducting a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons will not be affected in this trial.
Kerry, however, insisted that the NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: 'We are facing a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.'
There is a radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, blowing up things and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop this before it happens?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we have been informed of such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, US lawmakers will travel to Europe to dispel concerns about alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue to work with the US on counterterrorism efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
