It is very important to the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain on board in our joint efforts to combat terrorism, Murphy, a Democrat first-term senator and chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations and European Affairs subcommittee, said in an interview in Washington.
I'm also going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger at the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has intercepted millions of phone records in Europe have strained relations with some US allies, although the head of the intelligence service said this week that the reports were inaccurate and based on a misunderstanding of metadata collected by NATO allies and shared with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents provided by Snowden that the NSA had monitored the cell phones of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of the National Intelligence Service, James Clapper, defended espionage on allies as necessary and stated that it was common on both sides.
In the midst of all the commotion, Murphy said his agency is preparing for the trip to Congress this year and hopes the delegation will include members of both parties and the House.
The names of the other Members of Parliament will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact route is still being worked out.
